{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"6bf5b874-a2f6-49e1-9b89-3cf453f6eb3d","content":"Here's the equivalent command for Microsoft.Testing.Platform:\n\n```bash\ndotnet test \\\n  --filter \"Category=Integration\" \\\n  -- \\\n  --report-trx \\\n  --coverage --coverage-output-format cobertura \\\n  --crashdump \\\n  --hangdump --hangdump-timeout 5m\n```\n\nEverything after `--` is passed to the new platform runner.\n\n**Required NuGet packages** (add to your test project):\n\n| Old feature | New package |\n|---|---|\n| `--logger trx` | `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.TrxReport` |\n| `--collect \"Code Coverage\"` | `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.CodeCoverage` |\n| `--blame-crash` | `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.CrashDump` |\n| `--blame-hang` | `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.HangDump` |\n\nYou also need `Microsoft.Testing.Platform.MSBuild` to enable the new runner via `dotnet test`. Make sure your test project sets `<EnableMSTestRunner>true</EnableMSTestRunner>` (or `<TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>true</TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>` for non-MSTest frameworks) and targets `net8.0` with `<OutputType>Exe</OutputType>`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"5fafc6a6-9612-429f-a6dd-f0ab00a5429e","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about migrating their CI test command from VSTest to Microsoft.Testing.Platform (MSTest runner) on .NET 8. This is a knowledge question about .NET testing tooling migration, not a codebase task.\n\nLet me provide the equivalent command for Microsoft.Testing.Platform.\n\nKey differences when moving to Microsoft.Testing.Platform:\n1. `dotnet test` still works but the underlying runner changes\n2. Filter syntax changes: `--filter` → `--filter` (same flag but may need adjustment)\n3. Logger: `--logger trx` → `--report-trx` (built-in)\n\n\n4. Code coverage: `--collect \"Code Coverage\"` → `--coverage` with Microsoft.CodeCoverage package, or you can still use `--collect`\n5. Blame options like `--blame-crash` and `--blame-hang` have different equivalents\n\nThere are two ways to run tests with Microsoft.Testing.Platform: through `dotnet test` where it acts as an adapter, or by running the test executable directly. The CLI arguments differ depending on which approach you take, and with .NET 8+, you may need to pass arguments after `--` when using `dotnet test`.\n\nFor the platform's native flags, `--filter` stays the same, but `--logger trx` becomes `--report-trx` (requiring Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.TrxReport), code coverage shifts to `--coverage --coverage-output-format cobertura` (with Microsoft.CodeCoverage), and the blame options map to `--crashdump` and `--hangdump` with their respective packages. When invoking through `dotnet test` as the entry point, you'll pass these arguments differently than when running the executable directly. Now I'm mapping out the specific NuGet packages needed for each feature—the TRX reporting extension, the code coverage package, and the extensions for crash and hang dump diagnostics.","outputTokens":1109,"requestId":"0C03:2B0E8:217F86:274E1A:69F0053E"},"id":"676900d0-8972-4013-80e6-edf32d251dbf","timestamp":"2026-04-28T00:54:41.873Z","parentId":"a17cc59b-8bfc-4138-be54-009c61229718"}
